    "body": "### Problem\n\n### Is your feature request related to a problem?\n\nWhen working with long lines that are wrapped to fit the window, Neovim's default line-wise motion commands `(j, k, ^, $)` treat the wrapped parts as a single continuous line. This makes navigation cumbersome and inefficient. For instance, pressing j moves the cursor to the start of the next logical line, not the next visual line on the screen. This is a significant friction point for users who often work with wrapped text, such as markdown, documentation, or code with long comments.\n\n\n### Expected behavior\n\n\nI propose adding a new mode, similar to Emacs' \"visual line mode,\" that treats wrapped lines as distinct, navigable lines. This feature is documented [here](https://www.gnu.org/software/emacs/manual/html_node/emacs/Visual-Line-Mode.html).\n\nIn this mode, the following behaviours would be implemented:\n\nVertical Motion: j and k would move the cursor up and down by one visual line on the screen, not one logical line. This would allow users to navigate the wrapped text as it's displayed.\n\nHorizontal Motion: ^ and $ would move the cursor to the beginning and end of the visual line, respectively.\n\nThis would be a toggle-able option, similar to set wrap, so users could enable it as needed.",
